WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:04.600
Hi guys, my name is Zach, I work at Databricks, and I'm going to talk to you about how you

00:00:04.600 --> 00:00:10.680
can take your data that you've all hopefully got sitting there as part of your organisation

00:00:10.680 --> 00:00:16.120
and utilising that with LLMs to make it something more than the sum of its parts.

00:00:16.120 --> 00:00:21.320
So data isn't anything new, we all work with data more than likely, and it's important

00:00:21.320 --> 00:00:23.799
we get it, it's our jobs.

00:00:23.799 --> 00:00:29.240
Data is the new oil, we heard that for the last 15-20 years, but with ChatGPT for the

00:00:29.240 --> 00:00:34.040
last 18 months, everything started to change.

00:00:34.040 --> 00:00:38.080
And we've got this hype cycle, and it's pretty much here to stay, by the way.

00:00:38.080 --> 00:00:42.040
And at Databricks, we're seeing this story time and time again, which is your competitive

00:00:42.040 --> 00:00:45.919
advantage as a company is tied to your data maturity.

00:00:45.919 --> 00:00:51.439
So if we have this chart, on the x-axis we'll have data maturity, on the y we've got your

00:00:51.439 --> 00:00:55.840
competitive advantage, we paint this lovely picture where as you get more mature, you're

00:00:55.840 --> 00:00:58.560
going to be more competitive.

00:00:58.560 --> 00:01:00.320
And it's really about these two extremes.

00:01:00.320 --> 00:01:05.599
On the left, you've got this data silo where things are really hard, life is difficult,

00:01:05.599 --> 00:01:10.879
you've got lots of tooling, lines of business may not be communicating with one another,

00:01:10.879 --> 00:01:12.120
it's just difficult.

00:01:12.120 --> 00:01:16.199
And on the right-hand side, we have this polar opposite.

00:01:16.199 --> 00:01:22.239
Your data forward, you're using AI, you've got metrics, insights, everything you do in

00:01:22.239 --> 00:01:26.680
the company has got data as part of the decision.

00:01:26.680 --> 00:01:31.919
Everything wants to be on the right-hand side, you want to be on the right-hand side.

00:01:31.919 --> 00:01:36.720
Quick show of hands, who feels like they're in a company at the moment who's trying to

00:01:36.720 --> 00:01:38.320
be on the right-hand side?

00:01:38.320 --> 00:01:39.320
Yeah.

00:01:39.320 --> 00:01:42.279
There are a few of you.

00:01:42.279 --> 00:01:46.480
Keep your hand raised if that was done predominantly through competitive pressure, like, oh, if

00:01:46.480 --> 00:01:51.599
we don't do this, we're going to get left behind, we've got to go do this, our competitors

00:01:51.599 --> 00:01:55.320
are doing it, we've got to be doing it, everyone's doing it.

00:01:55.320 --> 00:01:56.320
Cool.

00:01:57.199 --> 00:02:00.919
And the last question here, which is how many of you have been in a meeting where you've

00:02:00.919 --> 00:02:05.080
been told by someone to work on a project, and you've heard something along the lines

00:02:05.080 --> 00:02:10.559
of we need to be doing more with AI, we can solve this problem with an LLM, can we do

00:02:10.559 --> 00:02:11.960
this?

00:02:11.960 --> 00:02:17.399
And leadership want to see AI features.

00:02:17.399 --> 00:02:22.279
So you end up in this situation where you've got all of the LLMs, you've been told you

00:02:22.279 --> 00:02:26.919
need to do something, and you have your data and the LLM.

00:02:26.919 --> 00:02:30.919
And the data is your competitive edge, like, hopefully no one else has this.

00:02:30.919 --> 00:02:35.919
I'm sure your company would be displeased if that data was with everyone else.

00:02:35.919 --> 00:02:39.279
And you've got to keep everything governed, of course.

00:02:39.279 --> 00:02:45.600
And you kind of end up naturally gravitating towards probably RAG, which is Retrieval Augmented

00:02:45.600 --> 00:02:46.600
Generation.

00:02:46.600 --> 00:02:50.600
And if you haven't, it's probably a good starting point as well.

00:02:50.600 --> 00:02:55.639
And the reason is, and we'll talk about what is RAG by looking at what it isn't to start

00:02:55.639 --> 00:02:56.800
with.

00:02:56.800 --> 00:03:00.759
So in a traditional LLM flow, we might ask a question, I've been hearing a lot about

00:03:00.759 --> 00:03:03.080
positron, what on earth is that?

00:03:03.080 --> 00:03:08.919
I'll ask that to the LLM, it gets fed in, and then we get an answer back.

00:03:08.919 --> 00:03:11.880
And in this case, this is not what I was expecting at all.

00:03:11.880 --> 00:03:16.839
I didn't want to know about the physics of an electron or its antimatter, whatever.

00:03:16.839 --> 00:03:19.800
What I wanted to know is about an IDE.

00:03:19.800 --> 00:03:25.279
Now for RAG, it's a little bit different, but it's pretty much the same.

00:03:25.279 --> 00:03:29.479
My question is still there, what is positron?

00:03:29.479 --> 00:03:31.759
But the difference is it has access to the data.

00:03:31.759 --> 00:03:35.600
You set it up so that it knows how to talk to your data.

00:03:35.600 --> 00:03:37.639
And this is where things get interesting.

00:03:37.639 --> 00:03:40.720
And this is where the retrieval part of the name comes from.

00:03:40.720 --> 00:03:44.039
It's looking for relevant documents.

00:03:44.039 --> 00:03:48.240
And then the augmentation part comes in, which is you're taking your original question and

00:03:48.240 --> 00:03:50.559
you're augmenting it with that data.

00:03:50.559 --> 00:03:56.399
So it might be you're an employee at Posit, and it's got access to all the internal documentation

00:03:56.399 --> 00:03:57.759
if this was a year ago.

00:03:57.759 --> 00:04:02.240
Or it might be that it's just got documentation from the website.

00:04:02.240 --> 00:04:05.839
And then you get back your answer, and that's the generative part.

00:04:05.839 --> 00:04:09.279
And in this case, that was what I was looking for.

00:04:09.279 --> 00:04:14.440
So the benefit here is you get to use the data with something that's already there, right?

00:04:14.440 --> 00:04:18.119
These models are there, you don't have to go and fine tune them or train them

00:04:18.119 --> 00:04:20.880
to do RAG, you can just add in your data and off you go.

00:04:20.880 --> 00:04:23.279
You kind of supercharged everything.

00:04:23.279 --> 00:04:25.000
And you can change that data in real time.

00:04:25.000 --> 00:04:26.279
It's flexible, it's dynamic.

00:04:26.279 --> 00:04:30.959
You don't have to go and train a model necessarily to keep things up to date.

00:04:30.959 --> 00:04:36.119
And in this case, the example here is kind of like a chatbot situation, but it doesn't need

00:04:36.119 --> 00:04:37.239
to be that either.

00:04:37.239 --> 00:04:41.279
It could be something for content generation or more in bold.

00:04:41.279 --> 00:04:42.079
So it sounds great.

00:04:42.079 --> 00:04:43.239
I love RAG.

00:04:43.239 --> 00:04:44.720
Let's do it.

00:04:44.760 --> 00:04:49.600
Maybe I can just shove everything into OpenAI and be on with my day.

00:04:49.600 --> 00:04:51.000
I know that they can do this.

00:04:51.000 --> 00:04:52.519
Let's do that.

00:04:52.519 --> 00:04:53.799
Sounds good.

00:04:53.799 --> 00:04:59.359
Oh, the legal and the security team have something to say about this.

00:04:59.359 --> 00:05:03.600
There's a lot of stringent requirements you probably have in your organization,

00:05:03.600 --> 00:05:07.880
and they want to make sure that you're following the internal guidelines.

00:05:07.880 --> 00:05:11.880
Things like data residency, industry-specific regulation,

00:05:11.880 --> 00:05:17.480
do you have to abide by HIPAA compliance or PCI or GDPR?

00:05:17.480 --> 00:05:19.119
You've got to have audit logs set up.

00:05:19.119 --> 00:05:22.399
You've got to have the model using the right license.

00:05:22.399 --> 00:05:25.519
It has to be for commercial use potentially.

00:05:25.519 --> 00:05:29.519
And then the security team is saying you've got to have SSO, and you've got to have everything

00:05:29.519 --> 00:05:33.239
remain within the organization tenancy and access controls.

00:05:33.239 --> 00:05:37.600
I mean, when I access the application, I should only be able to see what I'm allowed

00:05:37.600 --> 00:05:41.279
to see, not what necessarily you might be able to see.

00:05:41.279 --> 00:05:43.119
That's the big one.

00:05:43.119 --> 00:05:49.239
Monitoring and logging, encryption, and really it boils down to control and trust.

00:05:49.239 --> 00:05:54.040
You want to be in control, and you want to trust as little as you can.

00:05:54.040 --> 00:05:56.559
So things don't sound so simple anymore.

00:05:56.559 --> 00:06:00.480
I'm going to need more than just an API and my data.

00:06:00.480 --> 00:06:03.000
So what are the components that are required?

00:06:03.000 --> 00:06:05.239
It sounds like a lot.

00:06:05.239 --> 00:06:07.519
So the data, we get that.

00:06:07.519 --> 00:06:09.320
We've talked about it.

00:06:09.359 --> 00:06:14.000
You're going to need something to take that data and chunk it up into nice, lovely pieces.

00:06:14.000 --> 00:06:18.640
You might even want a place to train a model if you're so bold.

00:06:18.640 --> 00:06:23.000
You need a place to take those chunks and put them into what we call an embedding model

00:06:23.000 --> 00:06:25.480
to make what we call vectors.

00:06:25.480 --> 00:06:29.640
And you'll need a place to have the large language model, of course.

00:06:29.640 --> 00:06:32.040
Then you'll need a place to host those models.

00:06:32.040 --> 00:06:33.040
You need the vector database.

00:06:33.040 --> 00:06:34.920
You need a place to monitor it.

00:06:34.920 --> 00:06:37.600
You need a chain to tie it all together.

00:06:37.600 --> 00:06:38.600
You need an application.

00:06:38.880 --> 00:06:39.880
You need auditing.

00:06:39.880 --> 00:06:44.799
And then you'll need a place to host the application.

00:06:44.799 --> 00:06:46.399
It's still a lot, right?

00:06:46.399 --> 00:06:49.839
And how do you pull this all together and then keep in check?

00:06:49.839 --> 00:06:54.040
Well, thankfully, it's not as daunting as it sounds.

00:06:54.040 --> 00:06:59.640
So the tooling that I'll show you a quick example of today is PositConnect with a Python

00:06:59.640 --> 00:07:05.559
Shiny application and Databricks for the rest.

00:07:05.559 --> 00:07:08.640
And really, that'll be using something like a Lang chain combined with MLflow.

00:07:08.640 --> 00:07:10.279
I'm not going to show you any code.

00:07:10.279 --> 00:07:12.679
There's examples you can get that from links at the end.

00:07:12.679 --> 00:07:16.799
But really, Databricks will be handling all the things like the model serving, the vector

00:07:16.799 --> 00:07:21.679
database, the data processing, and making that compliant with all the logging and stuff

00:07:21.679 --> 00:07:22.880
that you need.

00:07:22.880 --> 00:07:26.519
And then Connect is going to have all the things behind your application secured and

00:07:26.519 --> 00:07:28.799
authenticated.

00:07:28.799 --> 00:07:31.959
So let's have a look at a little bit of a demo.

00:07:31.959 --> 00:07:43.119
So here, we're just going to go jump into PositConnect and click on my application.

00:07:43.119 --> 00:07:44.760
And I've got a little bit of a chat app here.

00:07:44.760 --> 00:07:47.160
It's using one of the new components from Python for Shiny.

00:07:47.160 --> 00:07:51.559
And the first thing is at the bottom, you can see that it's running as me.

00:07:51.559 --> 00:07:57.320
So I'm going to ask my question, which is how do I create an AIBI genie space?

00:07:57.320 --> 00:08:00.000
Now this is a preview feature in Databricks.

00:08:00.040 --> 00:08:03.640
It's not in the public documentation when the model was created.

00:08:03.640 --> 00:08:05.799
And my documents, I can't see them.

00:08:05.799 --> 00:08:11.239
So it really has no idea what's going on, or I would expect.

00:08:11.239 --> 00:08:14.000
It's giving me an answer.

00:08:14.000 --> 00:08:16.399
But it's not looking correct, right?

00:08:16.399 --> 00:08:20.160
There's no specific information that it found, but it's going to go ahead and try anyway,

00:08:20.160 --> 00:08:22.200
which is not really what I wanted.

00:08:22.200 --> 00:08:26.279
And if I turn off RAG with a flick of a switch, and I try the question again, it's just going

00:08:26.279 --> 00:08:27.279
to hallucinate.

00:08:27.279 --> 00:08:31.679
It's going to go and make up something, because it does what it can.

00:08:31.679 --> 00:08:37.320
So this is what I see, and this is not ideal, but it works to some extent, right?

00:08:37.320 --> 00:08:40.000
It's doing what we asked of it.

00:08:40.000 --> 00:08:46.880
Now if I flick a switch, and I go to look, next slide.

00:08:46.880 --> 00:08:51.359
If we go and look at what my colleague sees, so this is from a different point of view.

00:08:51.359 --> 00:08:53.400
So I have a colleague named Rafi.

00:08:53.400 --> 00:08:56.500
He works on the team closely with this feature.

00:08:56.500 --> 00:09:00.460
So hopefully he would have access to the data and know a little bit more about it.

00:09:00.460 --> 00:09:05.900
So if he goes ahead and he asks the same question, making sure RAG's enabled, it's going to tell

00:09:05.900 --> 00:09:07.020
him how to do it.

00:09:07.020 --> 00:09:08.500
It's going to have access to that data.

00:09:08.500 --> 00:09:12.099
It's going to find it, and it's all going to work correctly in giving the right response.

00:09:12.099 --> 00:09:16.260
And he can ask a follow-up question, and it's going to go and do the correct answer there,

00:09:16.260 --> 00:09:18.859
and it's going to give him a whole lot of steps.

00:09:18.859 --> 00:09:23.820
So the important thing here is that I've got something that's in PositConnect with Python

00:09:23.820 --> 00:09:28.460
Shiny, relatively straightforward, just hooked it up to the LLM, hooked it up to the chain

00:09:28.460 --> 00:09:33.820
that I had built with my data, and it was already going to have the correct access control

00:09:33.820 --> 00:09:43.179
that's going to be behaving as me or my colleague, and all the permissions are there as expected.

00:09:43.179 --> 00:09:48.380
The other nice bit is that when you're within PositConnect, you're going to have the, that's

00:09:48.380 --> 00:09:53.539
the right one, it's set so that everyone within the organization who's got access to Connect

00:09:54.140 --> 00:09:55.619
can see the app.

00:09:55.619 --> 00:09:58.340
I'm not trying to hide it to a specific subset of users.

00:09:58.340 --> 00:10:03.979
I'm relying on the integration with Databricks and PositConnect and authentication to do that,

00:10:03.979 --> 00:10:08.700
and all the nice logging that is there within PositConnect and auditing as well.

00:10:08.700 --> 00:10:13.739
Now, the nice thing that we have here within the Databricks side, one thing from the Databricks

00:10:13.739 --> 00:10:16.340
side I'll show you is what we call an inference table.

00:10:16.340 --> 00:10:20.900
So every time I'm asking a question to my application, I'm generating data.

00:10:20.900 --> 00:10:24.659
I've got the question I asked it and the answer, and it turns out when you go and train

00:10:24.659 --> 00:10:28.820
these models or you fine-tune them, that's the information that you need.

00:10:28.820 --> 00:10:32.140
So when you have these applications, you're actually creating kind of this cycle where

00:10:32.140 --> 00:10:36.539
you're generating data that you could later use whenever you're ready to go and improve

00:10:36.539 --> 00:10:39.780
something or at least monitor the situation.

00:10:39.780 --> 00:10:43.380
So here you can see an example of what that looks like in a table, and that's automatically

00:10:43.380 --> 00:10:44.380
done for me.

00:10:44.380 --> 00:10:48.539
I just have to toggle a box, and it goes and creates this table, and you can see that it's

00:10:48.539 --> 00:10:53.140
got the request, the response, who did it, and when, and all the other stuff.

00:10:53.140 --> 00:10:57.460
So an important component for the auditing, but very, very useful for that edge you want

00:10:57.460 --> 00:11:01.900
to create for yourself as an organization.

00:11:01.900 --> 00:11:07.580
So moving on and kind of looking at things in review from an architecture perspective,

00:11:07.580 --> 00:11:12.140
what we have is we have the users, they're integrated, and they're working with PositConnect

00:11:12.140 --> 00:11:13.900
and the application.

00:11:13.900 --> 00:11:18.340
They're working with Shiny, and they're using the application I've built, and in this case,

00:11:18.340 --> 00:11:24.099
it's using a positive SDK with one of the integrations for Databricks, and it's communicating

00:11:24.099 --> 00:11:28.940
with Databricks, and it's talking to this chain model that I've built, and it's doing

00:11:28.940 --> 00:11:35.340
it via an SDK that we have, and that chain goes and talks to all the other components

00:11:35.340 --> 00:11:39.979
on the Databricks side, which are the embedding model, the vector database, the LLM, and of

00:11:39.979 --> 00:11:44.460
course, the inference tables I just mentioned, and of course, the data as well.

00:11:44.460 --> 00:11:52.179
The data is feeding the vector database, and that's updating at will when I decide.

00:11:52.179 --> 00:11:57.020
From a governance and security perspective, we've made sure to tick all these boxes, and

00:11:57.020 --> 00:12:02.380
we've got the application again, and the first point of call is this SSO that we've got set

00:12:02.380 --> 00:12:03.380
up in PositConnect.

00:12:03.380 --> 00:12:09.380
I can only access this if I've got part of the organization, and it's going to automatically

00:12:09.380 --> 00:12:12.380
have my user credentials embedded.

00:12:12.539 --> 00:12:17.460
That token is going to be used for all of the processes within the application, and

00:12:17.460 --> 00:12:22.580
it's going to make sure that when I ask that question again, which is, what is Positron,

00:12:22.580 --> 00:12:28.059
and it does that check against the data, it's doing it as me, and it's only seeing what

00:12:28.059 --> 00:12:30.419
I should be able to see.

00:12:30.419 --> 00:12:34.020
We can regularly update that data from secure sources, and we don't have to worry about

00:12:34.020 --> 00:12:38.260
things going to people who aren't meant to see it.

00:12:38.260 --> 00:12:43.419
When we feed that to the model again for our augmentation phase, and we get our answer

00:12:43.419 --> 00:12:49.419
back, we've audited and logged all the actions that are going on.

00:12:49.419 --> 00:12:53.380
In summary, there's three pillars that we've gone through and things that you should probably

00:12:53.380 --> 00:12:57.219
think about, which is this data, and we know that it's your competitive advantage.

00:12:57.219 --> 00:13:01.659
I've mentioned it a bunch of times, and it's really when you combine it with the LLMs,

00:13:01.659 --> 00:13:06.820
you're starting to get something that's far more useful than both of the parts individually.

00:13:06.820 --> 00:13:10.580
It's really, really important that you do this potentially sooner rather than later,

00:13:10.580 --> 00:13:13.940
because you're going to be creating this cycle where you're generating data for yourself,

00:13:13.940 --> 00:13:18.219
and you can use that whenever you see fit.

00:13:18.219 --> 00:13:22.419
From the model perspective, we've got these open models, and you need to have something

00:13:22.419 --> 00:13:23.419
with a permissive license.

00:13:23.419 --> 00:13:27.859
You need to be very careful here, because not every model will let you use the outputs

00:13:27.859 --> 00:13:31.799
to do something like that cycle I just described.

00:13:31.799 --> 00:13:37.679
You want end-to-end control, or maybe your organization, and you want to be able to customize

00:13:37.679 --> 00:13:39.200
things as required.

00:13:39.200 --> 00:13:41.919
You don't want to relinquish control to a third party.

00:13:41.919 --> 00:13:45.799
You want to make sure that you're getting this data, because again, it is your competitive

00:13:45.799 --> 00:13:46.799
edge.

00:13:46.799 --> 00:13:52.159
From a governance and security perspective, we need to make sure that everything is behind

00:13:52.159 --> 00:14:00.320
authentication, and access controls are key here, and auto-logging.

00:14:00.320 --> 00:14:01.799
That's it from my side.

00:14:01.799 --> 00:14:02.799
Thank you.

00:14:02.799 --> 00:14:08.919
There's a QR code for some of the slides, and you'll find code for doing this in Databricks,

00:14:08.919 --> 00:14:12.400
and some of the examples from the Posit Connect side at some of those links.

00:14:12.400 --> 00:14:16.039
If you have any questions, you can either email me at that address, or come and find

00:14:16.039 --> 00:14:18.320
me for a chat.

00:14:18.320 --> 00:14:23.840
Thank you.

00:14:23.840 --> 00:14:24.840
Thank you, Zach.

