I guess it's just mainly the thought process about how you go about it.

00:15:24.000 --> 00:15:25.000
I think it just came up.

00:15:25.000 --> 00:15:26.000
Okay, yeah.

00:15:26.599 --> 00:15:27.599
Okay, yeah.

00:15:27.599 --> 00:15:32.280
With this one-stop solution, how can the end user get insights on the specifications of

00:15:32.280 --> 00:15:38.719
the Databricks black box?

00:15:38.719 --> 00:15:43.119
Not sure what you mean by the black box, but maybe we can have a chat about it.

00:15:43.119 --> 00:15:49.119
Okay, well, the board just came in, so it's funny how that happens, right?

00:15:49.119 --> 00:15:55.719
I can understand how connecting Databricks allow authentication and specific user access,

00:15:56.440 --> 00:16:00.239
but how can we get our organization on board with using an open source permissive model?

00:16:00.239 --> 00:16:03.239
What are some examples of these open source models?

00:16:03.239 --> 00:16:04.239
Yeah.

00:16:04.239 --> 00:16:10.520
So one of the best models that hits all the checkboxes in my mind at the moment would

00:16:10.520 --> 00:16:14.200
be obviously LLAMA 3.1 specifically.

00:16:14.200 --> 00:16:18.080
They changed the license slightly between 3 and 3.1.

00:16:18.080 --> 00:16:23.799
It's got kind of the most broad capabilities for you to do something with it as a model,

00:16:23.880 --> 00:16:27.440
but you can actually use the outputs to train something else yourself.

00:16:27.440 --> 00:16:31.799
Whereas if you're using like chat GPT and you will read the licensing, there's a gray

00:16:31.799 --> 00:16:35.840
area where it says like, hey, you can't use something that would compete with us, although

00:16:35.840 --> 00:16:38.239
you own the outputs and all these other various things.

00:16:38.239 --> 00:16:41.320
So you really will need to go and read the license.

00:16:41.320 --> 00:16:47.960
The good thing is, is with RAG, the model doesn't need to be the absolute best.

00:16:47.960 --> 00:16:49.520
Just needs to be pretty good.

00:16:49.719 --> 00:16:51.440
LLAMA 3.1 is pretty good.

00:16:55.200 --> 00:17:00.039
Can the data set stay in the local file system or must it go to Databricks?

00:17:00.039 --> 00:17:01.400
You can use whatever you want.

00:17:01.400 --> 00:17:03.840
You can do this without Databricks entirely.

00:17:03.840 --> 00:17:07.640
So if you wanted to use your own vector search locally and you had something like InductDB

00:17:07.640 --> 00:17:11.760
as a vector extension, many other databases have it now.

00:17:11.760 --> 00:17:13.760
You can use that.

00:17:13.760 --> 00:17:16.119
There's no requirements for this to be in Databricks at all.

00:17:16.119 --> 00:17:18.280
It's more about, again, you can do RAG anywhere.

00:17:18.280 --> 00:17:19.280
You can do it locally.

00:17:19.280 --> 00:17:23.800
It's just the example I showed was specific to Databricks from an enterprise perspective.

00:17:23.800 --> 00:17:24.800
Okay.

00:17:24.800 --> 00:17:27.079
I think we have time for one more question.

00:17:27.079 --> 00:17:30.560
What's your experience with setting sources with RAG?

00:17:30.560 --> 00:17:34.760
So you'll need to use a little bit of lang chain magic, I think, to make those come up.

00:17:34.760 --> 00:17:38.760
I didn't do it for my demo, but we have examples somewhere.

00:17:38.760 --> 00:17:43.199
So if you have a particular need for that, I can probably dig it up.

00:17:43.199 --> 00:17:46.560
Well, give it up to Zach, Zach at Databricks.

00:17:48.280 --> 00:17:49.280
Thanks.

00:17:49.280 --> 00:17:50.280
Bye.

